The ram is clearly identified through the elongated shape and long horns which emerge from the top of the head and curve around behind the narrow ears. The eyelids and snout of the ram have been clearly delineated, and the model has been executed to a high quality with a smoothed surface.   There are small chips notable at the top of the head and around the edges of the horns, and towards the mouth area the tips of the horns are broken off.

description.value:
Limestone figures of two uraeus cobras.

Both cobras wear the sun-disc crowns, and their eyes are simplistically rendered. Their hoods appear to not have any incised detail, though the lower portion of their bodies include two additional small uraeus cobra figures that wear sun-disc crowns with cow horns. Their lower bodies are raised up behind them and their tails are curled at the back. The right side cobra’s lower body has been damaged at the reverse, and the back of the base is also partly missing.

The surface of the limestone is heavily damaged and worn, with clear flaking across both the bodies of the cobras and across the sides of the base. The object is now supported by a thin modern base.

description.value: Plaster head of Tyche wearing mural crown.  A plaster head of a city Tyche: a strong-featured female head in high relief, looking slightly to her right. The pupils of the eyes are marked. Her hair is parted in the centre and hangs in tasselled locks on each side of the face. She wears a wreath of oakleaves and berries (not certainly acorns), behind which is a castellated diadem, with a background presumably of hair, but now very damaged. The back is plain and fairly flat. Some details of the back are hidden by the modern plaster used to mount the object on a stand.  Poured into a one-piece mould, with subsequent hand working: the wreath, because of the undercut behind it, must have been added. White plaster, now with a creamy coloured surface.

description.value: Granite head of a male official, the body and base of the statue now lost.   The figure wears a striated wig with a centre parting which partially covers the ears and appears to flare out slightly away from the face. The eyes are wide and almond shaped, with raised lines indicating the upper eyelids and elongated cosmetic lines at the outer eye. The thick eyebrows are flat across the brow and slope downwards at the temples, while the nose is broad and the cheeks are fleshy and rounded. The mouth is wide with sharply incised lips, and the outer corners are slightly upturned to suggest a small smile.  In addition to the break at the figure’s neck, there are numerous scratches at the neck and chin area. Thin cracks are visible across the left side of the statue from the cheek down to the neck, across the left eye, and another from the centre of the forehead down to the nose. Several small chips are also visible around the mouth of the statue.

description.value:
Black granite crown of the god Amun and rear pillar.

On one side of the sculpture is the two feathered crown of Amun, the outer edges now damaged. The opposing side features the back-pillar of the statue shaped like the top of an obelisk. At the top section is an image of the goddess Maat in sunken relief, shown wearing a long dress and holding a was sceptre. Above her is the sun disc with two uraeus cobras extending down on either side, with several ankh symbols linked together and extending down the obelisk, framing the goddess. Below this are two slim columns of incised text bearing the royal titulary of Ramesses II.

The edges of both the pillar and crown of Amun are chipped, and the top of the obelisk is slightly damaged. The object is now supported on a thick modern base.

description.value:
Limestone figure of a reclining woman.

She rests her head on a rectangular support, and faces out to one side. She wears a short Nubian style wig with clear traces of black paint. Her facial features are mostly worn, though the narrow shape of her eyes and a thin brow are outlined. She is depicted nude, with her right arm held by the side of her body while the left arm is raised towards her chest. She may have held an object in her left hand over her chest, but this is now obscured. The breasts and her arms have traces of a white paint across the surface. This is also found on her lower stomach and around the pubic area, which is clearly delineated. Her legs lie straight out and her feet are now missing. Around the edges of the reclining figure the recessed bed is heavily chipped and the stone is gouged at several sides and edges.

Her facial features are mostly worn, though the narrow shape of her eyes and a thin brow are outlined. She is depicted nude, with her right arm held by the side of her body while the left arm is raised towards her chest. She may have held an object in her left hand over her chest, but this is now obscured. The breasts and her arms have traces of a white paint across the surface. This is also found on her lower stomach and around the pubic area, which is clearly delineated. Her legs lie straight out and her feet are now missing. Around the edges of the reclining figure the recessed bed is heavily chipped and the stone is gouged at several sides and edges.

description.value: Limestone bust of a female figure, partially damaged.  She wears a large and heavy wig with detailed individual tresses of the hair and tighter braids of hair forming a pattern around the ends. Traces of black paint are still notable across the wig, while the top of the head also features a band or diadem decorated with a pattern of vertical lines. There are traces of red paint at the top of the head, possibly originally part of decoration from the top of the headband. Her eyes are heavily incised around the edges, with thick arched eyebrows and a slight depression conveying the brow bone. Her nose is now damaged at the tip, and her thick lips are pursed together. The bottom lip is sharply incised, and the outer corners of the mouth appear to be flat. There are faint traces of black paint within her eyes.   The edges of the wig closest to the face are broken off from the chin level, and there are further visible chips to her mouth and chin.

description.value:
Limestone head of a female figure, likely a sculptor’s model or trial piece.

She wears a long smooth lappet-wig which is tucked behind the ears, the ends of the wig are now lost. Her eyes are slim and her nose is broad at the tip. There are faint traces of back paint around the eyes and along the edges of the eyebrows. The mouth is small and the thick lips are pursed together, while the cheeks and jawline are rounded in appearance. On the reverse, the surface behind the ears and wig is a flat plane. There is a small square hole in the centre of this area.

There is a large break to the stone at the left side of the wig, and to the top of the head. There are chips and scratches to the face and neck, including damage to the tip of the nose, the upper lip, and across the forehead. There are various diagonal chips to the stone on the reverse, particularly towards the right side edge. The object has been attached to a modern rectangular base.

description.value: Blue glass intaglio with a portrait of Cleopatra VII: this pale blue glass gem shows a portrait of a royal woman, identified by the broad, knotted diadem. The hair is tied back in a bun in the usual Greek manner and the dress that the queen wears is also Greek in origin, with folds of drapery clearly visible. The headdress, however, is Egyptian in style and in the form of a triple uraeus; the cobras wear sun discs on their heads. The portrait features are relatively clear and show a full face, with straight nose and a strong chin with a downturned mouth. It is, however, the hairstyle and broad diadem in particular that indicate that this representation is of Cleopatra VII. Sardonyx intagio sealstone: the engraved design is of a draped, female bust, the hair bound by a double diadem formed by two strips worn close together but revealing the strands of hair in between. The hair is pulled back from the brow, and two rows of corkscrew locks frame the face, and then fall on to the shoulders. The eye that is shown is large. The downturned mouth and the short nose with flared nostrils compare with the marble portrait of a Ptolemaic queen which may represent Cleopatra II or III. The woman wears a garment that is pinned on her shoulder. The workmanship is fairly crude, but the composition is lively. Blue glass seal: the youth is shown with a prominent fringe of hair falling across the brow and temple; a long straight nose; small, angular chin; and the broad jaw and cheekbones that were to be such a strong feature of the portraits of Augustus. Beneath him is a cornucopia overflowing with fruit.

description.value: Circular die made of walrus ivory, engraved on both sides, with projecting lentoid handle at the top which is decorated on one side and plain on the other. Its tip is broken away. The decoration on the handle consists of the God the Father and Son enthroned over a prostrate human figure; above them is the damaged symbol of the Holy Ghost in the form of a dove. The matrix on this side is engraved with the half-length figure of a bearded man facing left in a circular frame, a sword held upright in his right hand, his cloak clasped at the shoulder. Perpendicular to it the impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.15 cm. The front side is convex and is covered in finger impressions. It shows a small part of a scarab-like seal impression, the signs are not well recognisable. A curved double line at the left, in the middle a vertical line, unrecognisable smaller signs in between, maybe a mn among them.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows a semi-circular convex surface, maybe from a leather bag. Two deep impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.25 cm is impressed in the rear. The upper side is flat at the top and bends downwards to the sides. At the flat part an almost complete oval scarab-like seal-impression is preserved with finger impressions around it. Visible are three columnsof hieroglyphs with a cartouche in the middle, from left to right: 1) nTr nfr nb tAwi 2) (MAa.t-kA-R')| nbw (Gardiner S12) 3) jTj(?)-HD (T25). 1) the good god, the lord of the two Lands 2) Hatshepsut 3) who takes the white crown(?). The same motif can be found twice on EA86816.

description.value: Very small fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a very glossy surface. The fragment is flat and shows impressions of a turned string with a width of 0.23cm on the rear. The seal bears a circumferential line and shows small seated lion with its head bent towards its back and parts of a rounded sign above it that is probably a sun disc. The rest is not preserved anymore.
